07560nam a22013815i 9780691232195DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20212004nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912321957 a10.1515/97806912321952doi  a(DE-B1597)583263  a(OCoLC)1257324324  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aMUS0200002bisacsh04a780/.9222200aShostakovich and His World /ced. by Laurel E. Fay. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (432 p.) :b6 halftones.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Bard Music Festival ;v5200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tPermissions -- tNote on Transliteration -- tPART I DOCUMENTS -- tShostakovich: Letters to His Mother, 1923-1927 -- tResponses of Shostakovich to a Questionnaire on the Psychology of the Creative Process -- tStalin and Shostakovich: Letters to a "Friend" -- t"The Phenomenon of the Seventh": A Documentary Essay on Shostakovich's "War" Symphony -- tPART II ESSAYS -- tShostakovich as Industrial Saboteur: Observations on The Bolt -- tThe Nose and the Fourteenth Symphony: An Affinity of Opposites -- tShostakovich and the Russian Literary Tradition -- tFried Chicken in the Bird-Cherry Trees -- tShostakovich and His Pupils -- tShostakovich's "Twelve-Tone" Compositions and the Politics and Practice of Soviet Serialism -- tListening to Shostakovich -- tINDEX -- tCONTRIBUTORS0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDmitri Shostakovich (1906-1975) has a reputation as one of the leading composers of the twentieth century. But the story of his controversial role in history is still being told, and his full measure as a musician still being taken. This collection of essays goes far in expanding the traditional purview of Shostakovich's world, exploring the composer's creativity and art in terms of the expectations--historical, cultural, and political--that forged them. The collection contains documents that appear for the first time in English. Letters that young "Miti" wrote to his mother offer a glimpse into his dreams and ambitions at the outset of his career. Shostakovich's answers to a 1927 questionnaire reveal much about his formative tastes in the arts and the way he experienced the creative process. His previously unknown letters to Stalin shed new light on Shostakovich's position within the Soviet artistic elite. The essays delve into neglected aspects of Shostakovich's formidable legacy. Simon Morrison provides an in-depth examination of the choreography, costumes, décor, and music of his ballet The Bolt and Gerard McBurney of the musical references, parodies, and "ations in his operetta Moscow, Cheryomushki. David Fanning looks at Shostakovich's activities as a pedagogue and the mark they left on his students' and his own music. Peter J. Schmelz explores the composer's late-period adoption of twelve-tone writing in the context of the distinctively "Soviet" practice of serialism. Other contributors include Caryl Emerson, Christopher H. Gibbs, Levon Hakobian, Leonid Maximenkov, and Rosa Sadykhova. In a provocative concluding essay, Leon Botstein reflects on the different ways listeners approach the music of Shostakovich.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aAgitprop.  aAndreev, Andrei.  aAtovmian, Levon.  aBabadzhanian, Arno.  aBaltin, Aleksandr.  aBasner, Veniamin.  aBelov, Gennadii.  aBloody Sunday.  aBrahms, Johannes.  aBusoni, Ferruccio.  aCarmen (Bizet).  aCarmina Bur ana (Orff).  aChekhov, Anton.  aChervinsky, Mikhail.  aChugaev, Aleksandr.  aCold War.  aCritical Realism.  aDante Alighieri.  aDargomyzhsky, Aleksandr.  aDenisov, E